information from the relations and place it in the
type field of the subject node.
We stress the fact that the relationship in the graph
can be also introduced to relate nodes that
identify the same concept. These relationships are
typed as ‘alias’ and are useful to connect pieces
of
information related to the same concept but referred
to in the text with different names (e.g
“William henry gates iii” is the alias of “Bill gates”
and vice versa ). The following image shows a table
representation of the SRO ["William henry gates iii",
"per:title", "magnate" ] stored in the graph.
Fact representation
The prolog Knowledge base is a conceptualization of
the neo4j database structure upon which is
possible, using the prolog programming language, retrieve
and present the information to the user
and infer new knowledge.
We can categorize the predicate into 4 different types.
name(ID,Name)
Considering the Database, the first thing we need
is a way to represent the list of entities i.e nodes
of
the graph. Each node can be identified by its identity
number and the associated name of the entity
which conceptualize. The predicate
name(ID,Name)
e.g
name(57,'microsoft'), describes the name of
the node identified by the identification number ID.
Using this conceptualization we are able to
handle the concept using the Identity number of the
nodes but we can always retrieve the string
value of the entity and present the information in
a meaningful and readable way.
type
(ID)
The type(id) predicate associates to each node its
type field. Since the type values of the nodes are
inherited by the KBP part of the system, we can have
two versions of this predicate:
organization
(ID),
person
(ID). This predicate allows us to distinguish
the organization from the person.
alias
(ID,ID_ALIAS)
